  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nNote upfront: this is a Python CLI/batch pipeline (fetch → filter → dedup → notify), not a React app, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply. I mapped that category onto the closest equivalent — redundant recomputation in hot loops — instead.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (`store.py:55-74`)\n\nFor every job in the batch (hundreds to low-thousands across boards like Microsoft/Amazon, which paginate up to 40×10 roles), you do a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, each as its own round trip through `sqlite3.Cursor.execute()`. This is the textbook N+1 — one query to check existence, then one write, per row, in a Python loop.\n\n```python\n# now: N SELECTs + N single-row writes\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nFix: batch the existence check with `WHERE key IN (...)` (chunked under SQLite's 999-param limit) and batch the writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        qmarks = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\", chunk)\n        existing.update((r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"]) for r in rows)\n\n    new, changed, touched, inserts, updates = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append(row)\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append(row)\n        else:\n            touched.append({\"key\": job.key, \"now\": now})\n\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title, url,\n            location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range, content_hash,\n            first_seen, last_seen) VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,\n            :location,:department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n            inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n            department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type, posted_at=:posted_at,\n            salary_range=:salary_range, content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now\n            WHERE key=:key\"\"\", updates)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\", touched)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(N/900) reads + 3 batched writes — the biggest win in the codebase given how large single-board dumps can get.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompilation per job (`filters.py:11-54`)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside** that per-job call — recompiling the same keyword regexes from scratch for every single job in the batch. For 1,000 jobs × 10 keywords, that's 10,000 `re.compile()` calls instead of 10.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])   # compiled once\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])   # compiled once\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nand change `match()` to accept the precompiled pattern lists directly (drop the `_compile()` calls from inside it). Same fix pattern the codebase already uses correctly for `_ATS_RULES` in `agent.py:150` — worth mirroring here.\n\n### 3. Caching opportunity — no conditional requests / HTTP caching (`fetchers.py`)\n\nThe pipeline runs on a 12h schedule (per git log) and does a **full re-fetch of every board every run** — including boards that paginate 30-40 sequential requests (Microsoft, Amazon, Google, Netflix, Optiver, Two Sigma) — even when nothing changed. Several of these APIs support conditional GET. Worth adding `ETag`/`If-None-Match` (or `Last-Modified`) caching per source URL, persisted in the `meta` table (which already exists for the scan marker), so unchanged boards short-circuit to a 304 instead of re-downloading and re-parsing the full payload.\n\n### 4. Redundant computation — serial pagination (`fetchers.py`, e.g. `fetch_amazon:718-738`)\n\nThe paginated fetchers (`fetch_google`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`) each `await` pages one at a time in a `for` loop:\n\n```python\nfor pg in range(max_pages):\n    data = await _get_json(client, url, params={..., \"offset\": pg * 10}, ...)\n    ...\n```\n\nThis is a sequential-request pattern analogous to N+1 — up to 40 round trips per board, each waiting on the previous. Amazon's `search.json` and Microsoft's `pcsx/search` both return a total count in their first response (`data[\"hits\"]`/similar) that you're currently discarding. You could fetch page 0, read the total, then fire the remaining pages concurrently (bounded by the existing `asyncio.Semaphore`) instead of serially — cutting wall-clock for large boards roughly N-fold. Google/Two Sigma/Optiver genuinely need serial paging since they stop on an empty page with no known total, so leave those as-is.\n\n### 5. Minor — sequential blocking notifier dispatch (`notify.py:105-109`)\n\n`dispatch()` runs Slack/webhook/email/SMS notifiers one after another, each doing a **synchronous** `httpx.post`/`smtplib` call (15s timeout each) inside what's otherwise an async pipeline. With multiple notifiers configured, worst case is ~60s of serial blocking at the very end of a run. Low priority since it's a batch script not a server, but if latency matters, converting these to `httpx.AsyncClient` calls run via `asyncio.gather` (each still wrapped in try/except so one failure doesn't kill the others) would parallelize them.\n\n### Not applicable / nothing found\n\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend in this repo — skipped.\n- **Memory leaks**: none found. `sqlite3` connections are always used via `Store`'s context manager, the `httpx.AsyncClient` in `fetch_all` is closed in a `finally` when it owns the client, and pagination loops are bounded by `max_pages` config — no unbounded growth.\n- **`Job.key`/`Job.content_hash` recomputation** (`models.py:55-69`): accessed 2-3× per job across `diff()`/`to_row()` (each recomputes a SHA-256 hash). Real but minor at this scale (thousands, not millions, of jobs) — only worth fixing if you fold it into the `store.diff()` rewrite above, since that refactor already computes `to_row()` once per job.\n\nThe `Store.diff()` batching (#1) is the one I'd prioritize — it's the clearest correctness-adjacent perf bug and directly touches every pipeline run.\n",
